description: Docker, CI/CD, and AWS deployment rules
globs: infra/**, docker/**, .github/**, deployment/**, terraform/**, ecs/**, aws/**
---

Deployment stack:
- Docker for packaging
- AWS for deployment (compute, storage, networking per docs/DEPLOYMENT.md)
- Supabase as managed PostgreSQL + auth/RLS (external to AWS; configure via env)
- Twilio for WhatsApp/SMS (external; credentials via env/secrets)
- Email provider (e.g. SendGrid or AWS SES) via env
- CI/CD for validation and release automation

DevOps rules:
- Applications must be container-friendly and stateless where possible.
- Keep builds reproducible; use environment-driven configuration.
- Separate build-time config from runtime config.
- Add health checks for API and workers; ensure logs are structured and production-usable.
- Support observability: system logs, AI response monitoring, latency, error tracking, usage analytics (see observability rule).

Docker expectations:
- Keep Dockerfiles clean and optimized; prefer multi-stage builds when useful.
- Avoid baking secrets into images; minimize image size where practical.

AWS expectations:
- Prefer managed services (ECS/EKS, RDS if needed, S3, SQS/SNS, etc.) per DEPLOYMENT.md.
- Use least-privilege IAM policies; make networking and environment assumptions explicit.
- Support observability via logs, metrics, and alarms; design for rollback-safe deployments.

CI/CD expectations:
- Run lint, tests, and build validation before merge/deploy.
- Keep deployment config version-controlled; use separate environments (e.g. dev/staging/prod).

Do not:
- Hardcode AWS resource IDs, Supabase URLs, or Twilio/OpenAI secrets in code.
- Mix deployment-only hacks into application logic.
- Assume local-only paths or config in production code.